            <h3>What is an argument?</h3>
            <p>An argument consists of a
                <strong>claim</strong>
                and a <strong>reason</strong>. In the simplest form, an argument can be read as:
                "Reason, therefore Claim" (or "Claim because Reason")
            </p>
            <p>In order to infer the claim from a reason, one needs a "bridge" - reasoning and logic
                that explains why the given reason supports the claim.</p>
            <p>However, in these HITs we are interested in claims that are <strong>not</strong>
                logically implied by the reason. We call them <strong>incorrect claims</strong>
                </p>
            <ul>
                <li>For
                instance, in an argument about taking an umbrella, the incorrect claim would be "We
                shouldn't take the umbrella" given the reason "It's about to start raining").
                </li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Your task: 2 steps</h3>

            <p>You see {{numberOfArguments}} arguments to different topics.</p>
            <p>First, you must select the <strong>incorrect claim</strong> (claim that does not
                logically follow the reason).</p>
            <ul>
                <li>If both claims are possible given the reason, select the claim which is more
                    likely to be incorrect.
                </li>
            </ul>

            <p>Second, write an <strong>explanation why</strong> the incorrect claim does not follow
                the reason.</p>


            <h4>Some examples</h4>

            <button class="btn btn-default" id="ex_toggle_examples">Show/hide examples</button>

            <div id="examples" class="example">

                <p>Argument about whether Marijuana is a gateway drug.</p>
                <p>Reason:
                    <em>Many patients have identified cannabis as an effective and safer alternative
                        to their prescription drugs.</em>
                </p>
                <p>( ) <em>"Marijuana is a gateway drug"</em><br/>
                    (o) <em>"Marijuana is a not gateway drug"</em>
                    (this claim should be selected as the incorrect one)
                </p>
                <p>Explanation: <em>None of these patients are also hardcore drug users.</em>

                <hr/>


                <p>Argument about grading colleges by the governmnet.</p>
                <p>Reason:
                    <em>Rank-ordering colleges isn't necessary, because each would use the same standardized scale.</em>
                </p>
                <p>( ) <em>"Government should not grade colleges"</em><br/>
                    (o) <em>"Government should grade colleges"</em>
                    (this claim should be selected as the incorrect one)
                </p>
                <p>Explanation: <em>Standardized scale is working well.</em>

                <hr/>

                <p>Argument about restaurant reservations for sale.</p>
                <p>Reason:
                    <em>Everyone should pay the same for the same thing.</em>
                </p>
                <p>( ) <em>"Restaurant Reservations Should Not Be for Sale"</em><br/>
                    (o) <em>"Restaurant Reservations Should Be for Sale"</em>
                    (this claim should be selected as the incorrect one)
                </p>
                <p>Explanation: <em>It is ethical that restaurants should offer equal treatment.</em>
            </div>


